    "caption": "An ancient nose on an ancient animal, snuffling through the jungle.",
    "shortDescription": "Tapirs have a short, flexible snout that they use like a tiny elephant trunk — perfect for grabbing leaves and pulling fruit off branches. They look a bit like a pig crossed with a rhinoceros, but they're actually most closely related to horses and rhinos. Tapirs are excellent swimmers and love to wade in rivers and lakes to cool down and escape insects. Fun fact: Baby tapirs are born with spotted-and-striped coats that make them almost invisible on the dappled rainforest floor."
